{{Infobox person | name = Ernests Brastiņš | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1892|10|15}} | birth_place = [[Pārgauja Municipality|Lielstraupes pagasts]], [[Governorate of Livonia]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1942|1|28|1892|10|15}} | death_place = [[Russian SFSR]], [[Soviet Union]] | nationality = Latvian | education = [[Saint Petersburg Art and Industry Academy|Stieglitz Art Academy]] | home_town = | occupation = Artist, museum director, religious leader | years_active = | spouse = }}
'''Ernests Brastiņš''' (19 March 1892–28 Januari 1942) was a Latvian artist, amateur historian, folklorist and archaeologist. He is known as the founder and driving force behind the [[Modern Paganism|neopagan]] religion [[Dievturība]], which he started in the 1920s and which was re-established after the fall of the Soviet Union.
== Biography == Ernests Brastiņš was educated at the [[Saint Petersburg Art and Industry Academy|Stieglitz Art Academy]] in [[Saint Petersburg]] in 1911-1915. After military service in [[World War I]] and the [[Latvian War of Independence]] he became the director of the [[Latvian War Museum]]. During his time at the museum he studied Latvian history, Latvian ethnography, folk art and symbols, and investigated around 300 Latvian hill forts and the folklore connected to them.<ref name="ozolins">Gatis Ozoliņš. 2014. "The Dievturi movement in Latvia as invention of tradition". ''Modern Pagan and Native Faith Movements in Central and Eastern Europe''. {{ISBN|9781317544616}}</ref>
In 1926 he officially founded the first [[Dievturība]] organization together with his sculptor brother. Dievturība is a [[Modern Paganism|neopagan]] religion based on the old Baltic religion, Latvian folk culture, and especially the folk songs known as ''[[Daina (Latvia)|dainas]]''. The word Dievturība roughly means "the people who hold or live according to God's laws". With its fokus on folklore and national character, the Dievturība movement carried on a cultural inheritance from the 19th-century [[Young Latvians]] movement.<ref name="ozolins" />
Brastiņš' published works include three books on Latvian folk songs (1928-1929) and ''Dievturu cerokslis'' ("The Intentions of Dievturi") (1932) which outlines the principles of Dievturība, modeled on ''[[Luther's Small Catechism]]''.<ref name="ozolins" /><ref name="opentheology">Anita Stasulane, Gatis Ozoliņš. [https://www.degruyter.com/downloadpdf/j/opth.2017.3.issue-1/opth-2017-0019/opth-2017-0019.pdf Transformations of Neopaganism in Latvia: From Survival to Revival]. ''[[Open Theology]]'' 2017; 3: 235–24.</ref> Having attracted prominent artists and intellectuals to the movement, Brastiņš unsuccessfully tried to have Dievturība adopted as the official state religion of Latvia.<ref>Suzanne Pourchier-Plasseraud. 2015. ''Arts and a Nation: The Role of Visual Arts and Artists in the Making of the Latvian Identity'', 1905-1940. p. 76. {{ISBN| 9789004300286}}</ref>
After the [[1934 Latvian coup d'état]] the movement was forced to re-register as a secular organization. Brastiņš' research as well as his religious engagements were terminated with the [[Soviet occupation of Latvia in 1940]].<ref name="ozolins" /> He was arrested by the Soviet security services on 6 July 1940. On 24 May 1941, he was sentenced to eight years in a correctional labour camp in Russia for having founded and led the Dievturība organization. He was put on another trial in Russia on 27 January 1942 and was sentenced to death.<ref name="opentheology" /> The execution was carried out the following day.<ref name="ozolins" />
== Legacy ==
[[File:Memorial stone of Ernests Brastiņš, founder of Dievturity, in Riga, Latvia v2.png|thumb|Ernests Brastiņš' monument in Riga, Kronvald Park, beside the congress hall at the city's canal.]]
During the Soviet era the Dievturība religion primarily lived on abroad in Latvian emigré communities. These varied in their view of it as a religion or just as a way to preserve Latvian traditions. The movement was officially re-registered in Latvia on 18 April 1990. Its contemporary adherents recognize Brastiņš as its founder and leading ideologue.<ref name="ozolins" />
